PROVIDED SOLUTION
The goal is to show that x ↦ ∫ y in Ioc 0 (2π), |log ‖f(circleMap 0 r x) - circleMap 0 1 y‖| is integrable on Ioc 0 (2π).

Proof strategy using MeasureTheory.Integrable.mono:

Step 1: Bound. For any c : ℂ and y ∈ [0, 2π]:
- ‖c - circleMap 0 1 y‖ ≤ ‖c‖ + 1 (triangle inequality, since ‖circleMap 0 1 y‖ = 1)
- So log ‖c - circleMap 0 1 y‖ ≤ log(‖c‖ + 1)
- And posLog ‖c - circleMap 0 1 y‖ ≤ log(‖c‖ + 1) (since ‖c‖ + 1 ≥ 1)

Step 2: Use |log x| = 2 * posLog x - log x, so:
∫ |log ‖c - e^{iy}‖| dy = 2 ∫ posLog ‖c - e^{iy}‖ dy - ∫ log ‖c - e^{iy}‖ dy

Step 3: By `circleAverage_log_norm_sub_const_eq_posLog`,
∫₀²π log ‖circleMap 0 1 y - c‖ dy/(2π) = posLog ‖c‖.
So ∫₀²π log ‖c - circleMap 0 1 y‖ dy = 2π posLog ‖c‖.

Step 4: ∫ posLog ‖c - e^{iy}‖ dy ≤ 2π log(‖c‖ + 1).

Step 5: Combining: ∫ |log ‖c - e^{iy}‖| dy ≤ 4π log(‖c‖ + 1) ≤ 4π(1 + posLog ‖c‖) ≤ 4π(1 + |log ‖c‖|).

Step 6: So x ↦ ∫ |log ‖f(circleMap 0 r x) - e^{iy}‖| dy ≤ 4π(1 + |log ‖f(circleMap 0 r x)‖|).

Step 7: The function x ↦ |log ‖f(circleMap 0 r x)‖| is integrable on Ioc 0 (2π) because f ∘ circleMap 0 r is meromorphic on any interval, so by `intervalIntegrable_log_norm_meromorphicOn`, log ‖f(circleMap 0 r ·)‖ is interval integrable on [0, 2π], hence |log ‖f(circleMap 0 r ·)‖| is also integrable (since integrability is preserved under absolute value for interval integrable functions: IntervalIntegrable.norm).

Step 8: Apply MeasureTheory.Integrable.mono with the bound 4π(1 + |log ‖f(circleMap 0 r x)‖|), which is integrable by step 7.
